Date: Fri 29 Sep 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Mercury News (CA) [edited]
<http://www.mercurynews.com/mld/mercurynews/news/local/states/california/northern_california/15637480.htm>

Natural Selection Foods, the company whose bagged spinach is at the
epicenter of a massive _E. coli_ outbreak across the country, on Thursday
announced that it has begun an aggressive testing plan similar to one
launched by the meat industry after Americans started dying from eating
hamburgers more than a decade ago. "We need to move to a different level of
food safety," said Charles Sweat, the company's chief operating officer.
Starting on Tue, 3 Oct 2006, all spinach, lettuce and other leafy greens
entering the company's processing plant in San Juan Bautista began
undergoing random sampling for _E. coli_, salmonella and other pathogens by
a third-party testing company. "It's like a fire wall that we're putting
between the fields and processing plant," Sweat said at a news conference
in a historic plaza next to the Old Mission in San Juan Bautista. Sweat
said he hoped his company would help develop new standards across the
produce industry -- which has been under severe criticism for not getting
ahead of a deadly problem it knew was simmering for years.
Natural Selection has hired a team of food-safety consultants. One of them,
microbiologist Mansour Samadpour, said that he was hopeful that the cause
of the E. coli contamination would be pinpointed, but it's possible that
Natural Selection and the American public may never know. He said the
random sampling plan will involve testing about 60 samples for each lot --
about 4 pallets -- of fresh produce. He said he didn't know what percentage
that represents, but that it's a standard developed by the International
Commission for Microbiological Specifications for Food."When you test the
product and it's positive, it's not going to go through the plant," he
said. "It's going to get dumped."
Before widespread publicity about _E. coli_ contamination began scaring
customers away from beef in the mid-1990s, the meat industry had also
resisted costly sampling programs. But the industry now embraces sampling.
Sweat said on Thursday that tests by state and federal investigators have
not turned up any evidence that the contamination was introduced at the San
Juan Bautista plant. He said his company would pay the "out of pocket"
medical expenses of people sickened by spinach packaged by Natural
Selection. The company has set up a toll-free number -- (888) 736-2840 --
so that people made ill by spinach can call for claim information.
The produce industry is also developing a set of voluntary food-safety
guidelines that it hopes will satisfy the FDA and other federal and state
regulators.
[byline: Ken McLaughlin and Lisa M. Krieger]
